2 INCREASE OF FINES FOR FAILURE TO STOP FOR A SCHOOL BUS AND
3 EXPANSION OF WHAT CONSTITUTES PRIMA FACIE EVIDENCE IN THOSE
4 CASES
5 SECTION 3.(a) G.S. 20-217 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 20-217. Motor vehicles to stop for properly marked and designated school buses in
7 certain instances; evidence of identity of driver.
8 …
9 (e) Except as provided in subsection (g) of this section, any person violating this section
10 shall be guilty of a Class 1 misdemeanor and shall pay a minimum fine of five hundred dollars
11 ($500.00). one thousand dollars ($1,000). A person who violates subsection (a) of this section
12 shall not receive a prayer for judgment continued under any circumstances.
13 …
14 (g) Any person who willfully violates subsection (a) of this section and strikes any person
15 shall be guilty of a Class I felony and shall pay a minimum fine of one thousand two hundred
16 fifty dollars ($1,250). four thousand five hundred dollars ($4,500). Any person who willfully
17 violates subsection (a) of this section and strikes any person, resulting in the death of that person,
18 shall be guilty of a Class H felony and shall pay a minimum fine of two thousand five hundred
19 dollars ($2,500).seven thousand dollars ($7,000).
20 …
21 (i) Whenever evidence is presented in any court or administrative hearing of the fact that
22 a vehicle was operated in violation of this section, it shall be prima facie evidence that the vehicle
23 was operated by the person in whose name the vehicle was registered at the time of the violation
24 according to the Division's records. If the vehicle is rented, then proof of that rental shall be prima
25 facie evidence that the vehicle was operated by the renter of the vehicle at the time of the
26 violation."
27 SECTION 3.(b) This section becomes effective December 1, 2025, and applies to
28 offenses committed on or after that date.
29
30 PROVISIONS REGARDING THE RECORDING, STORAGE, AND DISCLOSURE OF
31 VIDEO FROM DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION HIGHWAY CAMERAS
32 SECTION 4.(a) G.S. 132-1.1 is amended by adding a new subsection to read:
33 "(i) Highway camera video records stored by the Department of Transportation may not
34 be disclosed except as provided in G.S. 132-1.7B."
35 SECTION 4.(b) Chapter 132 of the General Statutes is amended by adding a new
36 section to read:
37 "§ 132-1.7B. Highway camera video records.
38 (a) Definitions. – The following definitions apply in this section:
39 (1) Disclose or disclosure. – To make a recording available for viewing or
40 listening to by the person requesting disclosure, at a time and location chosen
41 by the custodial law enforcement agency. This term does not include the
42 release of a recording.
43 (2) Highway camera. – A Department of Transportation video or digital camera,
44 located on highway right-of-way, for the purpose of monitoring vehicle
45 traffic.
46 (3) Personal representative. – A parent, court-appointed guardian, spouse, or
47 attorney of a person whose image or voice is in the recording. If a person
48 whose image or voice is in the recording is deceased, the term also means the
49 personal representative of the estate of the deceased person; the deceased
50 person's surviving spouse, parent, or adult child; the deceased person's
51 attorney; or the parent or guardian of a surviving minor child of the deceased.
Page 2 DRH30276-NDfa-7A

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (4) Recording. – A visual, or visual and audio, recording captured by a highway
2 camera.
3 (5) Release. – To provide a copy of a recording.
4 (b) Highway cameras shall record and store incidents upon the request of law
5 enforcement agencies to assist the following types of incident investigations along the interstates
6 and highways:
7 (1) Vehicle chases.
8 (2) Hit and run crashes.
9 (3) Road rage altercations.
10 (4) Street races.
11 (5) Street takeovers.
12 (6) Any other incident investigations of which law enforcement agencies feel the
13 assistance of this technology would support and expedite.
14 (c) Public Record Classification. – Recordings under this section are not public records,
15 as defined by G.S. 132-1.
16 (d) Disclosure; General. – Except as provided under subsection (b) of this section,
17 recordings shall be disclosed only as provided by this section. A person requesting disclosure of
18 a recording must make a written request to the Department of Transportation. The request shall
19 include the name of the person making the request, date and approximate time of the activity
20 captured in the recording, or otherwise identify the activity with reasonable particularity
21 sufficient to identify the recording to which the request refers. The Department may only disclose
22 a recording to the following:
23 (1) A person whose image or voice is in the recording.
24 (2) A personal representative of an adult person whose image or voice is in the
25 recording, if the adult person has consented to the disclosure.
26 (3) A personal representative of a minor or of an adult person under lawful
27 guardianship whose image or voice is in the recording.
28 (4) A personal representative of a deceased person whose image or voice is in the
29 recording.
30 (5) A personal representative of an adult person who is incapacitated and unable
31 to provide consent to disclosure.
32 When disclosing the recording, the Department shall disclose only those portions of the
33 recording that are relevant to the person's request. A person who receives disclosure pursuant to
34 this subsection shall not record or copy the recording.
35 (e) Disclosure; Factors for Consideration. – Upon receipt of the written request for
36 disclosure under subsection (d) of this section, as promptly as possible, the Department must
37 either disclose the portion of the recording relevant to the person's request or notify the requestor
38 of the decision not to disclose the recording to the requestor. The Department may consider any
39 of the following factors in determining if a recording is disclosed:
40 (1) If the person requesting disclosure of the recording is a person authorized to
41 receive disclosure pursuant to subsection (d) of this section.
42 (2) If the recording contains information that is otherwise confidential or exempt
43 from disclosure or release under State or federal law.
44 (3) If disclosure would reveal information regarding a person that is of a highly
45 sensitive personal nature.
46 (4) If disclosure may harm the reputation or jeopardize the safety of a person.
47 (5) If disclosure would create a serious threat to the fair, impartial, and orderly
48 administration of justice.
49 (6) If confidentiality is necessary to protect either an active or inactive internal or
50 criminal investigation or potential internal or criminal investigation.
DRH30276-NDfa-7A Page 3

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (f) Appeal of Disclosure Denial. – If the Department denies disclosure pursuant to
2 subsection (e) of this section, or has failed to provide disclosure more than three business days
3 after the request for disclosure, the person seeking disclosure may apply to the superior court in
4 any county where any portion of the recording was made for a review of the denial of disclosure.
5 The court may conduct an in-camera review of the recording. The court may order the disclosure
6 of the recording only if the court finds that the Department abused its discretion in denying the
7 request for disclosure. The court may only order disclosure of those portions of the recording that
8 are relevant to the person's request. A person who receives disclosure pursuant to this subsection
9 shall not record or copy the recording. An order issued pursuant to this subsection may not order
10 the release of the recording.
11 In any proceeding pursuant to this subsection, the following persons shall be notified and
12 those persons, or their designated representative, shall be given an opportunity to be heard at any
13 proceeding: (i) the head of the Department, (ii) any law enforcement agency personnel whose
14 image or voice is in the recording and the head of that person's employing law enforcement
15 agency, and (iii) the district attorney. Actions brought pursuant to this subsection shall be set
16 down for hearing as soon as practicable, and subsequent proceedings in such actions shall be
17 accorded priority by the trial and appellate courts.
18 (g) Release of Recordings; General; Court Order Required. – Except as provided under
19 subsection (b) of this section, recordings shall only be released pursuant to court order. Any
20 person requesting release of a recording may file an action in the superior court in any county
21 where any portion of the recording was made for an order releasing the recording. The request
22 for release must state the date and approximate time of the activity captured in the recording or
23 otherwise identify the activity with reasonable particularity sufficient to identify the recording to
24 which the action refers. The court may conduct an in-camera review of the recording. In
25 determining whether to order the release of all or a portion of the recording, in addition to any
26 other standards the court deems relevant, the court shall consider the applicability of all of the
27 following standards:
28 (1) Release is necessary to advance a compelling public interest.
29 (2) The recording contains information that is otherwise confidential or exempt
30 from disclosure or release under State or federal law.
31 (3) The person requesting release is seeking to obtain evidence to determine legal
32 issues in a current or potential court proceeding.
33 (4) Release would reveal information regarding a person that is of a highly
34 sensitive personal nature.
35 (5) Release may harm the reputation or jeopardize the safety of a person.
36 (6) Release would create a serious threat to the fair, impartial, and orderly
37 administration of justice.
38 (7) Confidentiality is necessary to protect either an active or inactive internal or
39 criminal investigation or potential internal or criminal investigation.
40 (8) There is good cause shown to release all portions of a recording.
41 The court shall release only those portions of the recording that are relevant to the person's
42 request and may place any conditions or restrictions on the release of the recording that the court,
43 in its discretion, deems appropriate.
44 In any proceeding pursuant to this subsection, the following persons shall be notified and
45 those persons, or their designated representative, shall be given an opportunity to be heard at any
46 proceeding: (i) the head of the Department, (ii) any law enforcement agency personnel whose
47 image or voice is in the recording and the head of that person's employing law enforcement
48 agency, and (iii) the district attorney. Actions brought pursuant to this subsection shall be set
49 down for hearing as soon as practicable, and subsequent proceedings in such actions shall be
50 accorded priority by the trial and appellate courts.
Page 4 DRH30276-NDfa-7A

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (h) Release of Recordings; Law Enforcement Purposes. – Notwithstanding any provision
2 of this section to the contrary, the Department shall disclose or release a recording to a district
3 attorney (i) for review of potential criminal charges, (ii) in order to comply with discovery
4 requirements in a criminal prosecution, (iii) for use in criminal proceedings in district court, or
5 (iv) for any other law enforcement purpose and may disclose or release a recording for suspect
6 identification or apprehension or to locate a missing or abducted person.
7 (i) Retention of Recordings. – The Department shall not be required to retain any
8 recording subject to the provisions of this section for more than 30 days, unless a court of
9 competent jurisdiction orders otherwise.
10 (j) No civil liability shall arise from compliance with the provisions of this section,
11 provided that the acts or omissions are made in good faith and do not constitute gross negligence,
12 willful or wanton misconduct, or intentional wrongdoing.
13 (k) Fee for Copies. – The Department may charge a fee to offset the cost incurred by it
14 to make a copy of a recording for release. The fee shall not exceed the actual cost of making the
15 copy.
16 (l) Attorneys' Fees. – The court may not award attorneys' fees to any party in any action
17 brought pursuant to this section.
18 (m) Use of Recordings. – Recordings subject to this section may not be used for fines or
19 private investigation.
20 (n) Elected Official. – No elected official may review recordings subject to this section,
21 unless they meet the criteria in subsection (d) of this section. This subsection does not apply to a
22 county sheriff or district attorney if review of the recordings is within the scope of a criminal
23 investigation."
24 SECTION 4.(c) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
25
26 FUND THE 24-HOUR OPERATION OF THE NORTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF
27 TRANSPORTATION METROLINA TRANSPORTATION MANAGEMENT CENTER
28 IN CHARLOTTE
29 SECTION 5.(a) There is appropriated from the Highway Fund to the Department of
30 Transportation the sum of three million dollars ($3,000,000) in recurring funds for the 2025-2026
31 fiscal year for the purpose of expanding the operational hours of the IMap and North Carolina
32 Department of Transportation Metrolina Transportation Management Center in Charlotte, North
33 Carolina, to 24 hours a day, every day of the year.
34 SECTION 5.(b) Of the funds appropriated from the General Fund to the Department
35 of Transportation for the 2025-2026 fiscal year, the sums of fifteen million dollars ($15,000,000)
36 in recurring funds and twenty million dollars ($20,000,000) in nonrecurring funds are allocated
37 to be used by the Department for the purpose of expanding the operational hours of the IMap and
38 North Carolina Department of Transportation Metrolina Transportation Management Center in
39 Charlotte, North Carolina, to 24 hours a day, every day of the year.
40 SECTION 5.(c) This section becomes effective July 1, 2025.
41
42 EFFECTIVE DATE
43 SECTION 6. Except as otherwise provided, this act is effective when it becomes
44 law.
